[!INFO] Reflection: NAFLD
While the pathophysiology of cirrhosis is fascinating, understanding it isn't of much practical use because once CLCD develops, prognosis is poor. (Particularly after the development of ascites and / or hepatic encephalopathy).
Management of these complications is challenging because they seem to recurr or become more frequent as CLCD progresses.
There, the take home message by the hepatologist on Curbsiders was to prevent cirrhosis from ever occuring, rather than struggling to treat it.
Probably, NASH must be a common aetiology among Sri Lankan women and men. In fact, it is .
It has overtaken alcohol as the leading cause of cirrhosis.
So when a patient comes to the ward,

  • assess for presence of metabolic syndrome
  • assess for risk of NAFLD with the FIB 4 and (other )Scores
  • If high risk, maybe refer to hepatologist / give dietary advice based on the readily available Sri Lankan dietary guidelines.

Pathogenesis of ascites

  • portal hypertension causes fluid to extravasate out of the hepatic sinusoids.
  • The liver oozes out fluid which collects in the peritoneum.

Effects of large volume paracentesis

  • LVP is arbitrarily defined as volume > 5 liters.
  • draining large volumes of ascitic fluid causes mechanical decompression of the splanchnic vessels leading to increased splanchnic flow. -> reduced systemic flow -> "paracentesis associated circulatory dysfunction".
  • the physical nature of this mechanism is demonstrated by amelioration of circulatory dysfunction after artificially increasing intra abdominal pressure with mechanical devices following LVP.
  • this is biochemically evidenced by raised renin levels seen 6 days after LVP.
  • These haemodynamic effects can affect renal function (hepatorenal syndrome) and the associated volume and electrolytes shifts can trigger hepatic encephalopathy.
  • albumin has been proven to reduce this circulatory dysfunction following LVP.
  • noradrenaline and terlipressin also have shown benefit.

pathogenesis of hepatorenal syndrome

  • Salt and water retention due to RAAS activation secondary to decreased "effective circulating volume" in the systemic circulation secondary to splanchnic vasodilation leads to renal hypoperfusion.
  • the kidneys "strangle themselves" of blood supply.

Hepatic encephalopathy

Pathogenesis

[!INFO] It's complex
It has a complex pathophysiology. See Source this Lancet article.

  • Although ammonia is central in the pathogenesis, measuring ammonia levels isn't clinically useful.
  • several precipitants have been identified.

Portal encephalopathy occurs in patients with portal to systemic shunting.
Examples: Cirrhosis, TIPS, or surgical shunts.

The synergistic action of ammonia with other toxins may account for many of the abnormalities occurring in liver failure, such as the changes in blood-to-brain transport of neurotransmitter precursors, the metabolism of amino acid neurotransmitters, and cerebral glucose oxidation. These changes may lead to activation of inhibitory (gamma-aminobutyric acid, serotonin) and impairment of excitatory (glutamate, catecholamines) neurotransmitter systems.

Increased aromatic amino acid to branch chained amino acids in plasma may contribute to hepatic encephalopathy. However, benefit or oral or IV branch chain amino acids is not clear.

Where does the ammonia come from?

  • The gastrointestinal tract is the primary source of ammonia.
  • It is produced by enterocytes by metabolism of glutamine
  • And by colonic bacterial catabolism of nitrogen containing molecules like protein and secreted urea.

Causes Precipitating Encephalopathy:

  • Infection
  • UGI bleed
  • Hypokalemia and / or metabolic alkalosis
  • Renal failure
  • Hypovolemia -> increases renal ammonia production
  • Hypoxia
  • Benzodiazepine use
  • Hypoxia
  • Constipation
  • Development of HCC / vascular occlusion.

Clinical features of hepatic encephalopathy

  • There is impairment of intellect, mood and personality change.
  • Subclinical encephalopathy is important to recognize.
    • identifed by subtle changes in number-connection tests, and digit-symbol and digit-copying tests.
    • see West Haven criteria
  • overt encephalopathy is what we usually identify in the wards, with flaps and reduced GCS.
  • Other features like confusion, agitation, slow speech etc.
  • Hyperreflexia and increased tone is a feature.
  • Fetor hepaticus : sweet smell to the breath.
  • Convulsions suggest an alternative diagnosis.
  • Asterexis, constructional apraxia, decreased mental function (impaired serial sevens test etc.)

Acute management of hepatic encephalopathy

#2020GM-NOV/Q29
Two main arms of management:

  1. Eliminate precipitating cause
  2. Reduce blood ammonia levels.
    • Lactulose, lactitol reduce absorption of ammonia from the gut by several mechanisms.
      • Lactulose is not broken down in the intestine because there is no specific enzyme for it. Therefore, it passes into the colon where it acts as osmotic particle and it's fermentation lowers colonic pH.
      • Lower pH -> NH3 -> NH4+ which is poorly absorbed.
      • Osmotic action produces diarrhoea -> increased faecal nitrogen excretion.
      • Lactulose is also a prebiotic.
    • Rifaximine - non absorbable antibiotic which ?reduces ammonia production by gut bacteria. Studies have shown that rifaximin + lactulose has better results than lactulose alone.
    • LOLA (L ornithing L aspartate) promotes ammonia metabolism.
    • Dietary protein restriction is NOT recommended.
    • Also, correct hypokalemia as hypokalemia increases renal ammonia production.
